=========================================================================
===== FINAL FINDINGS — 2026-05-21 =====
=========================================================================

ROOT CAUSE: DDR5 EXPO 6000 MT/s memory instability (silent bit-flips)
            on Ryzen 9950X + Corsair CMK96GX5M2E6000C36 (2x48GB) +
            ASUS X870E HERO BIOS 1401, with no ECC to detect/correct.

EVIDENCE:
1. PyArrow stress test: 2 silent data-corruption events in 100 iters
   under 25 GB memory pressure. Same file, different bytes returned.
2. memtester (30 GB locked): dozens of single-bit-flip failures detected
   at specific physical addresses (0xc3xxxxxx, 0xebxxxxxx, 0x142xxxxxx).
3. stress-ng vm (4 workers, 30 min): 2,110 bit errors total. All
   4 workers failed.
4. Kernel BUG event at 04:47:49 UTC during stress: "BUG: Bad page map",
   "unable to handle page fault", "scheduling while atomic". Followed by
   5 hours of RCU stalls -> system hung -> user had to force restart.
5. Temperatures within spec: DIMMs 71C under load (DDR5 throttle ~85C),
   CPU 89C peak (Tj_max 95C). Thermal not the primary cause.

EXPLAINS PRIOR FAILURES:
- 2026-05-19 04:09 kernel page-fault BUG -> cleanup-740 RCU stall
- cleanup-740 parquet p1_smoothed_winrate_hero corruption (6,482 cells)
- multitask-740 v1 ArrowInvalid length mismatch
- multitask-740 v2 attempt-2 NaN at val (bf16 logit corruption)
- multitask-740 v4 clean train.parquet rg6 silent corruption
- multitask-740 v5 val sidecar p1_items + p7_assists corruption
- multitask-740 v5 attempt-2 Blackwell segfault @ 2.5h
- NVIDIA DKMS compile segfault during apt install (this session)

REMEDIATION (priority order):
1. IMMEDIATE: Disable EXPO in BIOS. Run JEDEC default (4800 MT/s).
   Free. ~15% memory bandwidth loss for ML workloads. Should
   eliminate bit-flips. Test by re-running memtester to confirm.
2. If 4800 still errors: test each DIMM individually with memtest86+
   from USB. Could be a defective DIMM.
3. If 4800 stable: consider partial restore via JEDEC 5600 MT/s with
   loosened timings. May give back some bandwidth without instability.
4. PRODUCTION FIX: replace with ECC UDIMM kit (X870E HERO supports it).
   Kingston Server Premier KSM56E46BD8KM-48HM (48 GB ECC UDIMM 5600)
   is one valid option. ~$300-500 for 96GB pair. Hardware error
   detection/correction.
5. Check ASUS for X870E HERO BIOS newer than 1401 (May 2025).

PROCESSES KILLED BY USER'S FORCE RESTART:
- memtester PID 1238651 (had completed initial passes)
- stress-ng PID 1238652 (had completed 30-min run with 2110 errors)
- kernel_watch PID 1210360
- monitor PID 1210361

INVESTIGATION LOG: this file
SUPPORTING LOGS: memtester.log (380 MB), stress_ng.log, pyarrow_stress.log,
                 ssd_consistency.log, monitor.log, kernel_watch.log


=========================================================================
===== POST-JEDEC VALIDATION — 2026-05-21 12:19 UTC =====
=========================================================================

REMEDIATION APPLIED: User disabled EXPO in BIOS via Ai Tweaker -> Ai
Overclock Tuner -> Auto. RAM now runs at JEDEC default 4800 MT/s at
1.1V (was 6000 MT/s EXPO at 1.1V).

VALIDATION RESULTS (same tests that previously failed):

| Test                                | EXPO 6000 (before)        | JEDEC 4800 (after)    |
|-------------------------------------|---------------------------|-----------------------|
| memtester 30 GB, 1 pass             | hundreds of FAILUREs      | 0 failures            |
| stress-ng vm 4x5G, 30 min           | 2,110 bit errors          | 0 bit errors          |
| PyArrow round-trip 100 iter, 25 GB  | 2 silent data corruptions | 0 mismatches          |

TEMPERATURES (lower speed = less heat):
- DIMMs: 47-48°C under load (was 70-71°C at EXPO)
- CPU: 67-75°C peak under stress (was 89°C peak at EXPO)
- GPU: unchanged (idle ~47°C)

KERNEL EVENTS: ZERO new kernel BUGs, RCU stalls, page faults, or MCEs
during the 1h 45m validation suite. (Compare: previous run at EXPO
triggered a kernel page-fault BUG + 5-hour RCU stall that hung the
system.)

CONCLUSION: DDR5 EXPO 6000 MT/s on this Ryzen 9950X + Corsair
CMK96GX5M2E6000C36 (2x48GB) + ASUS X870E HERO BIOS 1401 combo was
the root cause of all reliability issues. JEDEC 4800 MT/s is stable.

Box is back in service for ML training workloads. Multi-hour Transformer
runs should now complete reliably, modulo the separate Blackwell torch
DataLoader bug (pytorch/pytorch#184062) which is still upstream.

BANDWIDTH IMPACT (4800 vs 6000 MT/s):
- Theoretical memory bandwidth: 4800/6000 = -20%
- ML training is rarely memory-bandwidth bound on Ada/Blackwell GPUs
  (compute-bound); expected real-world slowdown: 5-15% for typical
  Transformer/CNN workloads on RTX 5080.

OPEN: ECC RAM upgrade still recommended as the production-grade fix —
provides hardware error detection/correction even at higher speeds.
But JEDEC 4800 non-ECC is now empirically stable.


=========================================================================
===== PARQUET REBUILD VERDICT — 2026-05-21 17:19 UTC =====
=========================================================================

Both corrupted parquets rebuilt successfully on JEDEC 4800 MT/s RAM:

| File                                                                   | Build wall | Verification        |
|------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------:|---------------------|
| processed/player_features_prepatch_clean/{train,val}.parquet           | 2h 11m     | clean (all 13 rg)   |
| processed/rich_cols/{train,val}.parquet                                | 1h 34m     | clean (all 13 rg)   |

The new clean parquet md5 differs from the old corrupted backup
(d4789cdb... vs bdb7c8bc...), confirming the on-disk corruption was real
and the rebuild eliminated it. p9_days_since_last_log1p rg 6 — the
previously-unreadable column — now reads cleanly with sensible bounds
(min=0.010, max=5.903, all finite). Rich-cols pre/post-write
row-group-stats validation both passed; full pq.read_table on both
train and val succeeds in <1s.

OOM during clean-parquet build STEP 1 (rc=137) was the well-documented
post-write re-read pattern in cleanup-740's build_features.py
(aiserver2026-postwrite-parquet-reread-oom memory). The on-disk data
had already been written; the OOM happened during validation only.
Rich-cols sidecar build skips full re-read in favor of row-group-stats
verification and finished cleanly.

ZERO kernel events during ~3h 45m combined heavy-memory build time
(vs the catastrophic kernel BUG + 5h RCU stall during the same kind
of workload at EXPO 6000). RAM fix fully validated end-to-end.

